# Dataset Info

This project uses two datasets for two different parts of the analysis.

## 1. Credit Card Fraud Detection (Python anomaly detection)
**Source:** [Kaggle - mlg-ulb/creditcardfraud](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mlg-ulb/creditcardfraud)
**File:** `creditcard.csv`

Contains 284,807 transactions from European cardholders over a 2-day period in September 2013, with 492 labeled fraud cases. Features V1–V28 are PCA-transformed and anonymized for confidentiality; only `Time`, `Amount`, and `Class` (0 = genuine, 1 = fraud) are human-readable.

## 2. Credit Card Transactions Dataset (SQL rule-based flagging)
**Source:** [Kaggle - priyamchoksi/credit-card-transactions-dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/priyamchoksi/credit-card-transactions-dataset)
**File:** `credit_card_transactions.csv` (filename may vary slightly on download)

Contains transaction timestamp, amount, merchant, transaction category, and cardholder details — used for writing readable SQL queries since fields aren't anonymized.

## How to use
1. Download both CSVs from the links above (free Kaggle account required)
2. Place them in this `data/` folder, or load directly into your SQL/Python environment

## Why they're not committed directly
The `creditcard.csv` file in particular is large (~150MB) and exceeds typical GitHub file-size practice for portfolio repos. Both datasets are linked here rather than duplicated, in line with standard data project convention.
